The objective of the local development programme is to improve the livelihoods, health status, food and nutrition security of poor households, with a particular focus on women and vulnerable groups in 2 districts of Luwingu and Mbala.

description: A Consortium of 3 CGIAR centres: World Fish, Harvest Plus and CIFOR were supported to generate evidence based information, piloting appropriate agricultural technologies and improving local partners’ capacities in agriculture research, to feed into the Irish Aid Local Development Programme.

title: Civil Society For Public Service Delivery MISA-COMMUNITY RADIO
description: Ireland supports Zambian Chapter of the Regional NGO, Media Institute of Southern Africa (MISA) to support the capacity development of community radio stations in selected provinces in Zambia.

title: Grz (Government of Zambia) Capacity For Service Delivery UNITED NATIONS DELIVERING AS ONE
description: Ireland supported the UN in Zambia to deliver as one. This support enabled the UN system to deliver transformational results in support of national priorities as demanded by the global Sustainable Development Agenda 2030.

title: Grz (Government of Zambia) Capacity For Service Delivery IALDP (Irish Aid Local Development Programme) (National Programme)-LUWINGU & MBALA DISTRICTS
description: The Embassy provided support to the 2 local authorities of Mbala and Luwingu to strengthen their planning and implementation capacity and improved service delivery for local communities. The Provincial Planning Unit was supported to provide technical support and guidance to the district planning process.

title: Strengthen Grz (Government of Zambia) Financial Accountability OAG (Office of the Auditor General) - STRENGTHENING CAPACITY FOR SPECIALISED AUDITS
description: The support to the Office of the Auditor General’s Office enhances the capacity of the Supreme Audit Institution (SAI)- Zambia in implementation of forensic audit and investigations through the provision of forensic audit tools and training.

title: Strengthen Grz (Government of Zambia) Financial Accountability PARLIAMENTARY REFORM PROGRAMME
description: The National Assembly is supported to enhance oversight and legislative capacities of MPs in 3 selected Sessional Committees: - Committee on Education, Science and Technology, Committee on Health, Community Development and Social Services, and the Committee on Estimates and to increase access to parliamentary information.

title: Civil Society Programme Funding
description: Sustainable, positive change for poor and marginalised people and strengthened social accountability

title: Education Policy & Programming CAMPAIGN FOR FEMALE EDUCATION
description: Campaign for Female Education in Zambia supports child protection initiatives and strengthens communities’ capacity in promoting gender equity, protection of children, girls and women’s rights. The programme also provides bursaries to vulnerable girls.

title: Education Policy & Programming ZAMBIA OPEN COMMUNITY SCHOOLS
description: Ireland supports an NGO Zambia Open Community Schools that focuses on increasing access and improving the quality of education for Orphans and Vulnerable Children in Community Schools in order to enhance human capacity for sustainable national development.

title: Education Policy & Programming MINISTRY OF EDUCATION POOL FUND
description: Education Policy & Programming MINISTRY OF EDUCATION POOL FUND (Education Policy and Programming)

title: Education Policy & Programming Restless Development -HIV (Human Immunodeficiency Virus) SKILLS FOR TEACHERS
description: Restless Development contributes towards the improvement of quality delivery of education services and equity through implementation of HIV and AIDS activities in Colleges of Education throughout the country.

title: Increase capacity and resilience of poor people
description: Increase capacity and resilience of poor people

title: Programme Quality, Support & Development
description: Programme Quality, Support & Development primarily caters for programme costs that are administration in nature. Travel costs, salaries and other miscellaneouss programme expenditure are paid from this budgelines. Micro projects that contribute to the wider country programme are also funded from this budgetline.

title: Development, political, trade & economic relations
description: Strengthening the business environment in Kenya through a clearly defined trade promotion function delivered by the Embassy which contributes to improvements in trade and economic links with Ireland

title: Development, political, trade & economic relations
description: Embassy-led trade promotion and development cooperation initiatives contribute to inclusive economic growth, strengthened business environment and enhanced livelihoods and food security for farmers in Kenya

title: Support pro-poor economic development
description: Support to the design and launch of the Young Scientist Kenya Initiative which aims to promote learning of science amongst schoolchildren in Kenya

title: Programme Quality, Support & Devt
description: Programme Quality, Support & Devt

title: Palestinian Admin Areas - West bank and Gaza
description: Ireland’s programme in Palestine involves a combined focus on political action and humanitarian/development support. The overarching goal of the programme is a peaceful and prosperous Palestine and this is supported by two outcome areas dealing with our political and development engagement.

title: Vietnam Country Programme
description: The new Vietnam mission strategy takes a 'Whole of Embassy approach' and will continue to prioritise the promotion of our values through our development cooperation work but will also be more deliberate and ambitious in terms of our consular, economic and trade objectives not just for the benefit of Ireland but also in terms of pursuing a broader development agenda in Vietnam and the Mekong sub-region

title: Development Education
description: Working towards a sustainable and just world, by supporting development education partners to deepen citizens’ understanding of issues relating to global poverty, injustice and development, reflect on their responsibilities as global citizens and take action for a fairer and more sustainable future for all.

title: Election Monitoring
description: As part of Ireland’s commitment to sound electoral processes, Irish Aid supports the deployment of Irish observers on election observation missions led by the EU and the OSCE/ODHIR.

title: In Country Micro Projects
description: The In Country Micro Projects Scheme (ICMPS) enables Irish diplomatic missions in a number of countries, where Ireland does not have a development programme, to allocate funds to local civil society organisations for small development projects.

title: Civil Society Project Funding & Partnerships
description: The Civil Society Fund is a competitive project funding scheme primarily for Irish NGOs to carry out development projects overseas

title: Volunteer Related Programmes
description: Strengthening support for responsible volunteering, encouraging innovation and attracting interest from diverse groups of skilled volunteers

title: CERF (Central Emergency Response Fund) and Sudden Onset
description: Established in 2006, the CERF allocates funds at the most critical phase of an emergency – to kick start a humanitarian response, to respond to a sudden deterioration of a crisis, or to deliver life- saving humanitarian assistance in protracted crises that fail to attract sufficient resources.

title: Core Funding to OCHA (Office for the Coordination of Humanitarian Affairs ) & Red Cross
description: Core funding to Ireland’s main UN humanitarian coordination partner, the Office for the coordination of Humanitarian Affairs (OCHA), and core funding to the Red Cross Movement (International Committee of the Red Cross (ICRC) and International Federation of the Red Cross (IFRC))

title: Crisis Specific Appeals
description: Ireland’s humanitarian response and funding is directed to where needs are greatest in sudden onset, protracted and conflict related crises, with a particular emphasis on forgotten and underfunded emergencies.

title: Gender & Protection - Humanitarian
description: Gender and protection programming in humanitarian contexts is strengthened through strategic partnerships, based on robust appraisals, increased accountability and a focus on monitoring of results and performance. Promotion of advocacy, good practice and research to address gender-based violence (GBV) in emergencies is supported through key partners

title: Essential Services - Water and Sanitation
description: The Community Led Total Sanitation (CLTS) programme mobilises communities to completely eliminate open defecation.

title: Humanitarian Mine Action
description: Humanitarian mine action contributes to the overarching goal of saving and protecting lives and alleviating suffering, and other policy priorities including global hunger, fragile states and economic growth.

title: NGO (Non Governmental Organisations) Funding - HHP (Humanitarian Programme Plan), ERFS (Emergency Response Fund Scheme) & START Fund
description: Humanitarian response in predictable and protracted crises and recovery is supported by timely disbursal of funding to NGO partners working through the Humanitarian Programme Plan (HPP) 2017-18 funding mechanism and based on robust appraisal and a strengthened focus on accountability and monitoring of results and performance

title: Good Practice Portfolio
description: The Good Practice Portfolio (GPP) budget line supports Ireland’s international development policy’s emphasis on learning and building evidence to reduce poverty and deliver humanitarian assistance.

title: Refugee Resettlement Programme
description: Under this budget line, the resettlement of refugees in Ireland is supported by meeting the travel and related costs of refugees approved by the Minister for Justice & Equality to travel to Ireland to resettle here in 2017 under the UNHCR-led Refugee Resettlement Programme

title: Rapid Response Initiative
description: The Rapid Response Initiative budget line aims to assist in minimising the loss of life andalleviating the suffering of vulnerable people in crisis situations through the rapid deployment of emergency relief supplies and highly skilled personnel.

title: Fellowships
description: The Fellowship Training Programme aims to strengthen the capacity of development partner organisations in countries benefiting from Irish Aid support through the provision of higher education study opportunities. Fellowships are offered for full time Postgraduate Diploma/Master's level study either in Ireland or in region and there is a particular emphasis on linking fellowship awards to the key priorities of Irish Aid's country strategies in our partner countries.

title: Stability Fund
description: The Stability Fund provide support to a range of activities in developing countries recognising that stable secure environments are critical to enable post-crisis recovery and development to take place.

title: Africa Strategy / Trade
description: International trade has been key to Ireland's economic recovery, and the Programme for a Partnership Government includes a commitment to further develop trade with countries in Africa. We also see sustained and equitable economic growth that leads to employment, trade, investment and enhanced human well-being as essential in our poverty alleviation efforts. Supporting developing countries to grow in an inclusive way not only advances development but also advances Ireland's prosperity as well as that of our partners.

title: Essential Services - Education
description: Ireland supports the provision of quality basic education, improved learning and increased equity by strengthening education systems; by monitoring progress on global education goals, by generating evidence and analysis for improved practices and by supporting international assessments of quality and learning.

title: Essential Services - Health
description: Focus is on a portfolio of global, international and Irish initiatives, which have a proven ability to deliver results that improve health outcomes for the worlds' poorest.

title: Essential Services - HIV and AIDS (Human immunodeficiency virus infection and acquired immune deficiency syndrome)
description: Focus in providing support for the fight against AIDS, TB and Malaria by prioritising focus on health system strengthening, expanding reach into complex environments and engaging at country level. Monitoring at country level is also provided

title: Fragile States - Policy
description: Support for conflict prevention, peace negotiations and post-reconstruction particularly in sub-Saharan Africa. It also provides support to Security Sector Reform in countries threatened or affected by conflict and fragility.

title: Gender Equality & Women’s Empowerment
description: Reflecting Ireland's commitment to advancing gender equality and women's empowerment, funding supports a portfolio of partners and initiatives to address issues of gender inequality.

title: Governance & Human Rights
description: The Governance and Human Rights budget line provides funding to international partners working to improve governance and accountability internationally. There is a strong focus on improving tax systems, reducing illicit financial flows, strengthening institutions and improving transparency. Support to human rights partners through the Department provides valuable learning to inform our international engagement on human rights.

title: Inclusive Economies: Inclusive public policies
description: Focus is on strengthening social protection systems and on policy advocacy work at global level. It also includes support to agricultural research for development and people centred land governance with specific emphasis on securing equitable tenure rights of women, indigenous populations and pastoralist communities

title: Strategy Planning and Transparency
description: The Irish Aid programme is subject to regular internal and external monitoring. Irish Aid progresses incrementally towards full implementation of its aid transparency commitments. This budget line also contains payments to the International Aid Transparency Initiative (IATI). IATI is a voluntary, multi-stakeholder initiative that seeks to improve the transparency of aid, development, and humanitarian resources in order to increase their effectiveness in tackling poverty

title: Resilience - Climate Change
description: Support to the most vulnerable developing countries to address their adaption needs to climate change. Work will continue to increase understanding of, and protect, the rights of people forced into displacement due to climate change.

title: Resilience- Disaster Risk Recovery
description: Ensuring that disaster and climate risk information is available for planning adaptation and disaster risk reduction in LDCs.

title: Resilience - Nutrition
description: Investments address the World Health Assemby targets on nutrition and SDG2, with a focus on undernutrition challenges at country level. Funding is on programmes, knowledge gaps, and support for national nutrition coordination and policy across all contributing sectors and stakeholders.

title: Junior Professional Interns
description: The JPI scheme, which was launched in 2009 was developed to provide opportunities for qualified individuals to gain experience in the official aid programme. JPIs have been exposed to Irish Aid operations and programmes at headquarters, in selected missions, and in the Irish permanent missions to the United Nations and OECD. The JPI scheme has been recognised as an innovative way to build opportunities for young professionals who gain valuable experience in the workings of an international donor organisation leaving them well placed to find employment with Irish and international NGOs, the UN, and other international organisations.

title: Communications and Press
description: Delivery of communications materials, outreach events, engagement with print and media activities on Irish Aid activities, and management of Irish Aid website and social media platforms

title: Aid Effectiveness & Policy Coherence
description: In line with Ireland's policy commitments to aid effectiveness and policy coherence for sustainable development funding will be provided to support key processes and institutions central to improving the impact of development cooperation.

title: Core Contributions to OECD (Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development) DAC (Development Assistance Committee) & WG
description: Core commitments to OECD (Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development)Development Assistance Committee (DAC).

title: Technical Support Policy Unit
description: Technical support and expertise across the programme, including nutrition, social protection, education, economic inclusion, gender, and financing for development.

title: Development Research
description: Focus is in learning and building evidence to support the most effective approaches in reducing poverty.

title: Support to World Bank
description: The World Bank provides significant financial and technical support for developing countries in their efforts to eradicate poverty and achieve the SDGs. Ireland provides assessed contributions to the World Bank through the Department of Finance. Irish Aid supplements this with support for three programmes, supporting the poorest countries and those in fragile situations in their efforts to develop the private sector (identified in the 2015 Addis Ababa Conference on Financing for Development as critical to the implementation of the 2030 Agenda on Sustainable Development).

title: Food Security and Nutrition: FULL 2017 DISBURSEMENT - HQ PAY
description: Food Security and Nutrition: FULL 2017 DISBURSEMENT - HQ PAY

title: European Development Fund
description: The EDF is the main instrument for delivering EU development assistance to the African, Caribbean and Pacific Group of States (ACP) and the Overseas Countries and Territories (OCTs). It is governed by the Cotonou Agreement, which commits ACP countries to cooperation and dialogue with the EU on good governance, human rights and democratic principles and the rule of law.

title: Contributions to European Union Trust Funds
description: The migration and refugee crises have remained a key challenge for the EU and have led to the setting up of a number of dedicated trust funds such as the EU Trust Fund for Africa and the EU Turkey Refugee Facility, as elements of the EU’s response.

title: Other International Funds
description: Ireland supports three international organisations which provide specific support for agriculture and development; the independent assessment of Multilateral Organisations; and research and policy exchange between the EU and the Global South.

title: Aid For Trade
description: Ireland’s Aid for Trade support matches the commitment to continue to advocate strongly for the WTO, rule-based system to underpin economic, environmental and social development in developing countries; and to help developing countries improve their business and investment environment.

title: Programme Support & Development: CONSULTANCY WORK
description: Programme Support & Development: CONSULTANCY WORK

title: Assessed Contributions to United Nations Agencies
description: Assessed contributions are made to a number of UN agencies arising from Ireland’s membership of organisations such as the UN Industrial Development Organisation (UNIDO), the International Office for Migration (IOM), the UN Convention on Biodiversity (UNCBD), the UN Convention to Combat Desertification (UNCCD).

title: Voluntary Contributions to United Nations Agencies
description: Support is provided to a set of UN agencies whose work aligns closely to Ireland’s One World, One Future priorities on governance, human rights, social development and humanitarian action. Focus in 2018 will continue to be on the respective agencies’ contribution to the implementation of the 2030 Agenda at the country level and the reform of the UN development system. Contributions to these UN agencies are generally un-earmarked (directed to their core budgets), allowing them to plan and manage resources effectively in support of the policy objectives set out in their strategic plans

title: Management and Administration Costs
description: Administrative costs of development assistance programmes not already included under other ODA items as an integral part of the costs of delivering or implementing the aid provided

title: Teenage Pregnancy, SGBV (Sexual and Gender Based Violence) Services, Advocacy and Coordination
description: Activities under this budget line were devised to reduce the extremes of gender equality that exist in Sierra Leone, reinforced by the Irish Aid programme’s role in leading coordination of international partners’ policy and advocacy actions on gender equality, in particular on the issue of teenage pregnancy and pregnant teenage girls’ access to education.

title: Democratic Governance
description: This budget line's activities were devised to improve conditions for fair elections, enjoyment of human rights and equitable service provision in Sierra Leon

title: Programme Qualty, Support & Development
description: This is a process budget line used to support the quality and development of the Irish Aid programme in Sierra Leone.

title: More Sustainable Livelihoods for Women and Youth Improve Rural Livelihood
description: Activities under this budget support Markets for the poor approach in Tanzania and interventions which specifically focus on the economic empowerment of women and young people.

title: More Sustainable Livelihoods for Women and Youth Social Protection Programmes
description: Support interventions which enable national social protection instruments to have greater impact for women and youth and explore opportunities to provide direct support to the national social protection system.

title: Improved Reproductive Health for Women and Childre Improved Community Level Multi sectoral Nutrition
description: Allocation to support the implementation of the National Multisectoral Nutrition Action Plan. Support to national and local government levels in select regions for planning, budgeting and coordination to address malnutrition and stunting, especially among pregnant women and young children.

title: Improved Reproductive Health for Women and Childre Strengthen Reproductive Maternal &Child Health
description: Support national health systems that better respond to the needs of women, mothers and children- through TZ Health Basket Fund. Promote deployment of trained Community Health Workers in selected regions. To build national referral systems for high-risk pregnancies and disabilities

title: Programme Support Development
description: Costs for programme staff salaries and travel; for research, process fund, consultancy support, and the Head of Mission Fund.

title: Democratic space for G.Governance,Human Rights & G Strengthen Coalition &Community Response to Promot
description: This budget line for ;  Provisison of support to community level initiatives and generate evidence on ways to protect and prevent women and girls from experiencing gender based violence. Support women’s movement building and collective action at grassroots and national level around specific issues.Support to strategic partners including the media and parliamentarians.

title: Targeted Response to Regional Political and Humani Support Refugee and Host Communities

title: Enhanced Institutional Partnerships and Cooperatio Build Education & Innovation relationships btwn TZ
description: Strengthened approach to building education and innovation relationships between Tanzania and Ireland.

title: Educational Linkages, networks and cooperation
description: 1) Enhanced life skills of students in technical vocational education. 2) Poost graduate fellowships to 15 selected students for study in Ireland. 3)Increased links between Ireland and South African higher education and training institutions.

title: Opposition to gender based violence and support
description: 1) Improved coordination of CSOs working in GBV response. 2) Increased community capacity to demand access to justice and primary violence prevention.

title: Differentiated political relationship with South Africa
description: Strengthened analysis and evidence on regional governance, political economy and human security available and disseminated.

title: Support pro poor economic development
description: This budget line is supporting the realisation of the Young Scientists Kenya pilot in Kenya in 2018

title: Opposing GBV (Gender Based Violence) and support to survivors
description: Partners working within and across countries better able to generate and apply evidence and good practice on the intersectionalities of Gender, HIV and Human rights.

title: Better access to key health and disability service
description: This budget line concerns disadvantaged women and girls better able to access key health and disability services.

title: South Africa REGIONAL PROGRAMME ADMINISTRATION General Management And Administration
description: This is the budget line of South Africa REGIONAL PROGRAMME ADMINISTRATION General Management And Administration

title: CSO (Civil Society Organisations) capacity to promote governance & human rights
description: Strengthened capacity of CSOs to engage effectively and promote good governance and human rights in Zimbabwe.

title: Opposition to GBV (gender based violence) and support to survivors
description: 1) Enhanced coordination of GBV structures at national and provincial level to provide services to GBV survivors and their communities. 2) Improved CSO capacity to deliver coordinated HIV, GBV and livelihoods at community level.

title: Improved access and attainment of quality health
description: This is the budget line providing rehabilitation and recovery of public health services in Zimbabwe - Health Development Fund

title: Programme Administration, Support & Development
description: This budget line concerns Programme Administration, Support & Development of the Irish Aid programme in Zimbabwe

title: Improved Livelihoods Options
description: Ireland supports vulnerable children and children affected by HIV and AIDS through the awareness, care and support services provided by Households in Distress, a Zambian NGO with links to Irish missionaries.

title: Improved Livelihoods Options
description: The Embassy supports an Irish NGO Self Help Africa to implement its Local Development Programme in Northern Province. The objective of the local development programme is to improve the livelihoods, health status, food and nutrition security of poor households, with a particular focus on women and vulnerable groups in 2 districts of Luwingu and Mbala.

title: Strengthen Political & Bilateral relations
description: Further develop our political, economic and cultural relations, as well as seek new opportunities for trade and investment,  and further ways of connecting with and better serving the Irish community in both Zambia and Namibia.

title: Sustainable expansion of social protection program
description: Ireland will support the scale up of the National Social Cash Transfer Programme, support the UN through a joint funding mechanism to strengthen government to deliver the programme, support social accountability and children living with disabilities.

title: Increased availability of locally produced foods
description: Ireland will support Increased and diversified agricultural production and processing to increase the availability of locally produced, nutritious foods for Zambians

title: Increased access to education and relevant skills
description: The Mission will support skills training for youth and women through provision of financial support and support bursaries to keep poor rural girls in school

title: Programme Quality, Support & Devt
description: This funding covers the following costs: Programme Staff salaries; Programme staff Travel and Subsistence; Programme Development; HoM Fund - to implement micro projects on education, health, HiV/AIDS; and Africa Strategy. A saving of

title: Devt, political, trade & economic relations
description: This is the budget line for implementation of the Ireland Kenya Agri-food Strategy, support to trade promotion, institutional partnerships and sstrengthening of the business environment in Kenya

title: Kenya - Programme Quality and Support
description: This budget line concerns programme administation, monitoring and evaluation and the Embassy's microprojects (HoMs' Fund)

title: Nigeria Country Programme
description:
1. Life- saving assistance provided to vulnerable communities in Nigeria
2. Increased engagement in humanitarian and food security crises in Nigeria

title: Palestinian Admin Areas - West bank and Gaza
description: Ireland’s programme in Palestine involves a combined focus on political action and humanitarian/development support. The overarching goal of the programme is a peaceful and prosperous Palestine and this is supported by two outcome areas dealing with our political and development engagement.

title: Programme Quality & Support - Vietnam
description: This is a process budget line used to support the quality and development of the Irish Aid programme in Vietnam, Cambodia, Laos and Myanmar

title: Management and Administration Costs
description: Administrative costs of development assistance programmes not already included under other ODA items as an integral part of the costs of delivering or implementing the aid provided

title: Economic growth is more inclusive, sustainable and
description: Funds are provided through the Irish Development Experience and Sharing (IDEAS) programme to (1) targeted technical scholarships and (2) institutional partnerships between Ireland and Vietnam supporting knowledge transfer and capacity development.

title: Civil Society Partnerships
description: Funds are provided to Civil Society Partners to strengthen their capacity to engage effectively and promote good governance and human rights in Vietnam and the Mekong Sub-Region

title: Vietnamese ethnic minority household economies
description: Funds are provided to (1) Support the Government of Vietnam’s National poverty reduction programme, P135, targeted in poor ethnic minority communities promoting local level economic development. (2) Provide multi-annual support to a small number of agencies working in the targeted provinces (Helen Keller, Plan International,Care International, Oxfam Vietnam, RIC and UN Women) to pilot and scale up new models in ethnic minority empowerment: their focus will be on voice and participation, integrated nutrition response, gender empowerment and climate-sensitive development.

title: Regional Support Environmental, economic, health
description: Funds are provided to a range of UN and NGO partners to address fragillty and support sustainable development models in Vietnam, Cambodia, Laos and Myanmar. Given the context of unexploded ordnance/mines and under-nutrition/stunting in the targeted countries, humanitarian mine action and addressing hunger and under-nutrition has been a high priority focus for the regional programme.

title: Development Education
description: Working towards a sustainable and just world, by supporting development education partners to deepen citizens’ understanding of issues relating to global poverty, injustice and development, reflect on their responsibilities as global citizens and take action for a fairer and more sustainable future for all.

title: Election Monitoring
description: As part of Ireland’s commitment to sound electoral processes, Irish Aid supports the deployment of Irish observers on election observation missions led by the EU and the OSCE/ODHIR.

title: In Country Micro Projects
description: The In Country Micro Projects Scheme (ICMPS) enables Irish diplomatic missions in a number of countries, where Ireland does not have a development programme, to allocate funds to local civil society organisations for small development projects.

title: Misean Cara
description: Irish Aid provides support to Misean Cara, the umbrella body for missionary organisations in Ireland to carry out development projects

title: Civil Society Programme Funding
description: Sustainable, positive change for poor and marginalised people and strengthened social accountability

title: Civil Society Project Funding & Partnerships
description: The Civil Society Fund is a competitive project funding scheme primarily for Irish NGOs to carry out development projects overseas

title: Volunteer Related Programmes
description: Strengthening support for responsible volunteering, encouraging innovation and attracting interest from diverse groups of skilled volunteers

title: CERF (Central Emergency Response Fund) and Sudden Onset
description: The Central Emergency Response Fund (CERF) is a UN humanitarian funding instrument, managed by the UN Office for the Coordination of Humanitarian Affairs (UNOCHA). It releases money rapidly when a crisis occurs or when there is a sudden escalation of an existing crisis and responds to underfunded emergencies. It is a rapid response mechanism that aims to have funds on the ground within 72 hours of a crisis occurring, thereby kick-starting life-saving humanitarian response. It also strengthens core elements of humanitarian response in underfunded crises by responding to critical gaps.

title: Core Funding to OCHA (Office for the Coordination of Humanitarian Affairs ) & Red Cross
description: Core funding to Ireland’s main UN humanitarian coordination partner, the Office for the coordination of Humanitarian Affairs (OCHA), and core funding to the Red Cross Movement (International Committee of the Red Cross (ICRC) and International Federation of the Red Cross (IFRC))

title: Crisis Specific Appeals
description: Ireland’s humanitarian response and funding is directed to where needs are greatest in sudden onset, protracted and conflict related crises, with a particular emphasis on forgotten and underfunded emergencies.

title: Gender & Protection - Humanitarian
description: Gender and protection programming in humanitarian contexts is strengthened through strategic partnerships, based on robust appraisals, increased accountability and a focus on monitoring of results and performance. Promotion of advocacy, good practice and research to address gender-based violence (GBV) in emergencies is supported through key partners

title: Humanitarian Mine Action
description: Humanitarian mine action contributes to the overarching goal of saving and protecting lives and alleviating suffering, and other policy priorities including global hunger, fragile states and economic growth.
sector: Removal of land mines and explosive remnants of war

title: NGO (Non Governmental Organisations) Funding - HHP (Humanitarian Programme Plan), ERFS (Emergency Response Fund Scheme) & START Fund
description: Humanitarian response in predictable and protracted crises and recovery is supported by timely disbursal of funding to NGO partners working through the Humanitarian Programme Plan (HPP) 2017-18 funding mechanism and based on robust appraisal and a strengthened focus on accountability and monitoring of results and performance

title: Good Practice Portfolio
description: The Good Practice Portfolio (GPP) budget line supports Ireland’s international development policy’s emphasis on learning and building evidence to reduce poverty and deliver humanitarian assistance.

title: Refugee Resettlement Programme
description: Under this budget line, the resettlement of refugees in Ireland is supported by meeting the travel and related costs of refugees approved by the Minister for Justice & Equality to travel to Ireland to resettle here under the UNHCR-led Refugee Resettlement Programme

title: Rapid Response Initiative
description: The Rapid Response Initiative budget line aims to assist in minimising the loss of life andalleviating the suffering of vulnerable people in crisis situations through the rapid deployment of emergency relief supplies and highly skilled personnel.

title: Stability Fund
description: The Stability Fund provide support to a range of activities in developing countries recognising that stable secure environments are critical to enable post-crisis recovery and development to take place.

title: Africa Strategy / Trade
description: International trade has been key to Ireland's economic recovery, and the Programme for a Partnership Government includes a commitment to further develop trade with countries in Africa. We also see sustained and equitable economic growth that leads to employment, trade, investment and enhanced human well-being as essential in our poverty alleviation efforts. Supporting developing countries to grow in an inclusive way not only advances development but also advances Ireland's prosperity as well as that of our partners.

title: Essential Services - Education
description: Ireland supports the provision of quality basic education, improved learning and increased equity by strengthening education systems; by monitoring progress on global education goals, by generating evidence and analysis for improved practices and by supporting international assessments of quality and learning.

title: Essential Services - Health
description: Focus is on a portfolio of global, international and Irish initiatives, which have a proven ability to deliver results that improve health outcomes for the worlds' poorest.

title: Programme Research & Development Zambia
description: Programme Research & Development Zambia

title: Essential Services - HIV and AIDS (Human immunodeficiency virus infection and acquired immune deficiency syndrome)
description: Focus in providing support for the fight against AIDS, TB and Malaria by prioritising focus on health system strengthening, expanding reach into complex environments and engaging at country level. Monitoring at country level is also provided

title: Fellowships
description: The Fellowship Training Programme aims to strengthen the capacity of development partner organisations in countries benefiting from Irish Aid support through the provision of higher education study opportunities. Fellowships are offered for full time Postgraduate Diploma/Master's level study either in Ireland or in region and there is a particular emphasis on linking fellowship awards to the key priorities of Irish Aid's country strategies in our partner countries.

title: Gender Equality & Women’s Empowerment
description: Reflecting Ireland's commitment to advancing gender equality and women's empowerment, funding supports a portfolio of partners and initiatives to address issues of gender inequality.

title: Governance & Human Rights
description: The Governance and Human Rights budget line provides funding to international partners working to improve governance and accountability internationally. There is a strong focus on improving tax systems, reducing illicit financial flows, strengthening institutions and improving transparency. Support to human rights partners through the Department provides valuable learning to inform our international engagement on human rights.

title: Inclusive Economies: Inclusive public policies
description: Focus is on strengthening social protection systems and on policy advocacy work at global level. It also includes support to agricultural research for development and people centred land governance with specific emphasis on securing equitable tenure rights of women, indigenous populations and pastoralist communities

title: Resilience - Climate Change
description: Support to the most vulnerable developing countries to address their adaption needs to climate change. Work will continue to increase understanding of, and protect, the rights of people forced into displacement due to climate change.

title: Resilience - Nutrition
description: Investments address the World Health Assemby targets on nutrition and SDG2, with a focus on undernutrition challenges at country level. Funding is on programmes, knowledge gaps, and support for national nutrition coordination and policy across all contributing sectors and stakeholders.

title: Junior Professional Interns
description: The JPI scheme, which was launched in 2009 was developed to provide opportunities for qualified individuals to gain experience in the official aid programme. JPIs have been exposed to Irish Aid operations and programmes at headquarters, in selected missions, and in the Irish permanent missions to the United Nations and OECD. The JPI scheme has been recognised as an innovative way to build opportunities for young professionals who gain valuable experience in the workings of an international donor organisation leaving them well placed to find employment with Irish and international NGOs, the UN, and other international organisations.

title: Communications and Press
description: Delivery of communications materials, outreach events, engagement with print and media activities on Irish Aid activities, and management of Irish Aid website and social media platforms

title: Strategy Planning and Transparency
description: The Irish Aid programme is subject to regular internal and external monitoring. Irish Aid progresses incrementally towards full implementation of its aid transparency commitments. This budget line also contains payments to the International Aid Transparency Initiative (IATI). IATI is a voluntary, multi-stakeholder initiative that seeks to improve the transparency of aid, development, and humanitarian resources in order to increase their effectiveness in tackling poverty

title: Aid Effectiveness & Policy Coherence
description: In line with Ireland's policy commitments to aid effectiveness and policy coherence for sustainable development funding will be provided to support key processes and institutions central to improving the impact of development cooperation.

title: Core Contributions to OECD (Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development) DAC (Development Assistance Committee) & WG
description: Core commitments to OECD (Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development)Development Assistance Committee (DAC).

title: Technical Support Policy Unit
description: Technical support and expertise across the programme, including nutrition, social protection, education, economic inclusion, gender, and financing for development.

title: Development Research
description: Focus is in learning and building evidence to support the most effective approaches in reducing poverty.

title: Support to World Bank
description: The World Bank provides significant financial and technical support for developing countries in their efforts to eradicate poverty and achieve the SDGs. Ireland provides assessed contributions to the World Bank through the Department of Finance. Irish Aid supplements this with support for three programmes, supporting the poorest countries and those in fragile situations in their efforts to develop the private sector (identified in the 2015 Addis Ababa Conference on Financing for Development as critical to the implementation of the 2030 Agenda on Sustainable Development).

title: European Development Fund
description: The EDF is the main instrument for delivering EU development assistance to the African, Caribbean and Pacific Group of States (ACP) and the Overseas Countries and Territories (OCTs). It is governed by the Cotonou Agreement, which commits ACP countries to cooperation and dialogue with the EU on good governance, human rights and democratic principles and the rule of law.

title: Contributions to European Union Trust Funds
description: The migration and refugee crises have remained a key challenge for the EU and have led to the setting up of a number of dedicated trust funds such as the EU Trust Fund for Africa and the EU Turkey Refugee Facility, as elements of the EU’s response.

title: Other International Funds
description: Ireland supports three international organisations which provide specific support for agriculture and development; the independent assessment of Multilateral Organisations; and research and policy exchange between the EU and the Global South.

title: Aid For Trade
description: Ireland’s Aid for Trade support matches the commitment to continue to advocate strongly for the WTO, rule-based system to underpin economic, environmental and social development in developing countries; and to help developing countries improve their business and investment environment.

title: Assessed Contributions to United Nations Agencies
description: Assessed contributions are made to a number of UN agencies arising from Ireland’s membership of organisations such as the UN Industrial Development Organisation (UNIDO), the International Office for Migration (IOM), the UN Convention on Biodiversity (UNCBD), the UN Convention to Combat Desertification (UNCCD).

title: Voluntary Contributions to United Nations Agencies
description: Support is provided to a set of UN agencies whose work aligns closely to Ireland’s One World, One Future priorities on governance, human rights, social development and humanitarian action. Focus in 2018 will continue to be on the respective agencies’ contribution to the implementation of the 2030 Agenda at the country level and the reform of the UN development system. Contributions to these UN agencies are generally un-earmarked (directed to their core budgets), allowing them to plan and manage resources effectively in support of the policy objectives set out in their strategic plans

title: Ireland's Bilateral Programme in Nigeria
description: Humanitarian Response Fund

title: Palestinian Admin Areas - West bank and Gaza
description: Ireland’s programme in Palestine involves a combined focus on political action and humanitarian/development support. The overarching goal of the programme is a peaceful and prosperous Palestine and this is supported by two outcome areas dealing with our political and development engagement.

title: Economic growth is more inclusive, sustainable and
description: Funds are provided through the Irish Development Experience and Sharing (IDEAS) programme to (1) targeted technical scholarships and (2) institutional partnerships between Ireland and Vietnam supporting knowledge transfer and capacity development.

title: Civil Society Partnerships
description: Funds are provided to Civil Society Partners to strengthen their capacity to engage effectively and promote good governance and human rights in Vietnam and the Mekong Sub-Region

title: Vietnamese ethnic minority household economies
description: Funds are provided to (1) Support the Government of Vietnam’s National poverty reduction programme, P135, targeted in poor ethnic minority communities promoting local level economic development. (2) Provide multi-annual support to a small number of agencies working in the targeted provinces (Helen Keller, Plan International,Care International, Oxfam Vietnam, RIC and UN Women) to pilot and scale up new models in ethnic minority empowerment: their focus will be on voice and participation, integrated nutrition response, gender empowerment and climate-sensitive development.

title: Regional Support Environmental, economic, health
description: Funds are provided to a range of UN and NGO partners to address fragillty and support sustainable development models in Vietnam, Cambodia, Laos and Myanmar. Given the context of unexploded ordnance/mines and under-nutrition/stunting in the targeted countries, humanitarian mine action and addressing hunger and under-nutrition has been a high priority focus for the regional programme.

title: Programme Quality And Support Vietnam
description: This is a process budget line used to support the quality and development of the Irish Aid programme in Vietnam, Cambodia, Laos and Myanmar

title: Development Education
description: Working towards a sustainable and just world, by supporting development education partners to deepen citizens’ understanding of issues relating to global poverty, injustice and development, reflect on their responsibilities as global citizens and take action for a fairer and more sustainable future for all.

title: Election Monitoring
description: As part of Ireland’s commitment to sound electoral processes, Irish Aid supports the deployment of Irish observers on election observation missions led by the EU and the OSCE/ODHIR.

title: In Country Micro Projects
description: The In Country Micro Projects Scheme (ICMPS) enables Irish diplomatic missions in a number of countries, where Ireland does not have a development programme, to allocate funds to local civil society organisations for small development projects.

title: Misean Cara
description: Irish Aid provides support to Misean Cara, the umbrella body for missionary organisations in Ireland to carry out development projects

title: Volunteer Related Programmes
description: Strengthening support for responsible volunteering, encouraging innovation and attracting interest from diverse groups of skilled volunteers

title: CERF and Sudden Onset
description: The Central Emergency Response Fund (CERF) is a UN humanitarian funding instrument, managed by the UN Office for the Coordination of Humanitarian Affairs (UNOCHA). It releases money rapidly when a crisis occurs or when there is a sudden escalation of an existing crisis and responds to underfunded emergencies. It is a rapid response mechanism that aims to have funds on the ground within 72 hours of a crisis occurring, thereby kick-starting life-saving humanitarian response. It also strengthens core elements of humanitarian response in underfunded crises by responding to critical gaps.

title: Core Funding to OCHA & Red Cross
description: Core funding to Ireland’s main UN humanitarian coordination partner, the Office for the coordination of Humanitarian Affairs (OCHA), and core funding to the Red Cross Movement (International Committee of the Red Cross (ICRC) and International Federation of the Red Cross (IFRC))

title: Crisis Specific Appeals
description: Ireland’s humanitarian response and funding is directed to where needs are greatest in sudden onset, protracted and conflict related crises, with a particular emphasis on forgotten and underfunded emergencies.

title: Gender & Protection - Humanitarian
description: Gender and protection programming in humanitarian contexts is strengthened through strategic partnerships, based on robust appraisals, increased accountability and a focus on monitoring of results and performance. Promotion of advocacy, good practice and research to address gender-based violence (GBV) in emergencies is supported through key partners

title: Junior Professional Interns
description: The JPI scheme, which was launched in 2009 was developed to provide opportunities for qualified individuals to gain experience in the official aid programme. JPIs have been exposed to Irish Aid operations and programmes at headquarters, in selected missions, and in the Irish permanent missions to the United Nations and OECD. The JPI scheme has been recognised as an innovative way to build opportunities for young professionals who gain valuable experience in the workings of an international donor organisation leaving them well placed to find employment with Irish and international NGOs, the UN, and other international organisations.

title: Humanitarian Mine Action
description: Humanitarian mine action contributes to the overarching goal of saving and protecting lives and alleviating suffering, and other policy priorities including global hunger, fragile states and economic growth.

title: NGO Funding - HHP, ERFS & START
description: Humanitarian response in predictable and protracted crises and recovery is supported by timely disbursal of funding to NGO partners working through the Humanitarian Programme Plan (HPP) funding mechanism and based on robust appraisal and a strengthened focus on accountability and monitoring of results and performance

title: Refugee Resettlement Programme
description: Under this budget line, the resettlement of refugees in Ireland is supported by meeting the travel and related costs of refugees approved by the Minister for Justice & Equality to travel to Ireland to resettle here under the UNHCR-led Refugee Resettlement Programme

title: Rapid Response Initiative
description: The Rapid Response Initiative budget line aims to assist in minimising the loss of life andalleviating the suffering of vulnerable people in crisis situations through the rapid deployment of emergency relief supplies and highly skilled personnel.

title: Stability Fund
description: The Stability Fund provide support to a range of activities in developing countries recognising that stable secure environments are critical to enable post-crisis recovery and development to take place.

title: Africa Strategy  / Trade
description: The Africa Strategy and Innovation Fund supports the broad objectives of the Government’s Africa Strategy and the Global Ireland policy, which commits to doubling Ireland’s global footprint. It also supports innovative approaches to the implementation of Ireland’s new policy for international development, ‘A Better World’. These policies provide an increased impetus to expand our bilateral relationships, deepen our political engagement, innovate with our development cooperation and continue to seek opportunities for trade and investments in Africa. Increasing trade with countries in Africa, and supporting their inclusive and sustainable economic growth, is a focus of the Africa Strategy and Innovation Fund.

title: Essential Services  - Education
description: Ireland supports the provision of quality basic education, improved learning and increased equity by strengthening education systems; by monitoring progress on global education goals, by generating evidence and analysis for improved practices and by supporting international assessments of quality and learning.

title: Essential Services - Health
description: Focus is on a portfolio of global, international and Irish initiatives, which have a proven ability to deliver results that improve health outcomes for the worlds' poorest.

title: Essential Services  - HIV and AIDS
description: Focus in providing support for the fight against AIDS, TB and Malaria by prioritising focus on health system strengthening, expanding reach into complex environments and engaging at country level. Monitoring at country level is also provided

title: Fellowships
description: Through the Ireland Fellows programme, early career professional women and men, with leadership potential, from eligible countries may avail of relevant postgraduate study opportunities in Irish higher education institutions. On completion of their studies, graduates will have acquired relevant skills and knowledge and be better capacitated and positioned to influence the advancement of national social, economic and development priorities in their home country.

title: Gender Equality & Women’s Empowerment
description: Reflecting Ireland's commitment to advancing gender equality and women's empowerment, funding supports a portfolio of partners and initiatives to address issues of gender inequality.

title: Governance & Human Rights
description: The Governance and Human Rights budget line provides funding to international partners working to improve governance and accountability internationally. There is a strong focus on improving tax systems, reducing illicit financial flows, strengthening institutions and improving transparency. Support to human rights partners through the Department provides valuable learning to inform our international engagement on human rights.

title: Inclusive Economies:  Inclusive public policies
description: Focus is on strengthening social protection systems and on policy advocacy work at global level. It also includes support to agricultural research for development and people centred land governance with specific emphasis on securing equitable tenure rights of women, indigenous populations and pastoralist communities

title: Resilience - Climate Change
description: Support to the most vulnerable developing countries to address their adaption needs to climate change. Work will continue to increase understanding of, and protect, the rights of people forced into displacement due to climate change.

title: Resilience - Nutrition
description: Investments address the World Health Assemby targets on nutrition and SDG2, with a focus on undernutrition challenges at country level. Funding is on programmes, knowledge gaps, and support for national nutrition coordination and policy across all contributing sectors and stakeholders.

title: Communications and Press
description: Delivery of communications materials, outreach events, engagement with print and media activities on Irish Aid activities, and management of Irish Aid website and social media platforms

title: Strategy Planning and Transparency
description: The Irish Aid programme is subject to regular internal and external monitoring. Irish Aid progresses incrementally towards full implementation of its aid transparency commitments. This budget line also contains payments to the International Aid Transparency Initiative (IATI). IATI is a voluntary, multi-stakeholder initiative that seeks to improve the transparency of aid, development, and humanitarian resources in order to increase their effectiveness in tackling poverty

title: Core Contributions to OECD  DAC  &  WG
description: Core commitments to OECD (Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development)Development Assistance Committee (DAC).

title: Technical Support  Policy Unit
description: Technical support and expertise across the programme, including nutrition, social protection, education, economic inclusion, gender, and financing for development.

title: Research
description: Focus is in learning and building evidence to support the most effective approaches in reducing poverty.

title: European Development Fund
description: The EDF is the main instrument for delivering EU development assistance to the African, Caribbean and Pacific Group of States (ACP) and the Overseas Countries and Territories (OCTs). It is governed by the Cotonou Agreement, which commits ACP countries to cooperation and dialogue with the EU on good governance, human rights and democratic principles and the rule of law.

title: Contributions to EU Trust Funds
description: The migration and refugee crises have remained a key challenge for the EU and have led to the setting up of a number of dedicated trust funds such as the EU Trust Fund for Africa and the EU Turkey Refugee Facility, as elements of the EU’s response.

title: Other International Funds
description: Ireland supports three international organisations which provide specific support for agriculture and development; the independent assessment of Multilateral Organisations; and research and policy exchange between the EU and the Global South.

title: Aid For Trade
description: Ireland’s Aid for Trade support matches the commitment to continue to advocate strongly for the WTO, rule-based system to underpin economic, environmental and social development in developing countries; and to help developing countries improve their business and investment environment.

title: SOCIAL PROTECTION: UN OCHA, ADDIT'L CONTRIBUTION INTERNATIONAL TRADE CENTRE
description: SOCIAL PROTECTION: UN OCHA, ADDIT'L CONTRIBUTION INTERNATIONAL TRADE CENTRE

title: Assessed Contributions to UN Agencies
description: Assessed contributions are made to a number of UN agencies arising from Ireland’s membership of organisations such as the UN Industrial Development Organisation (UNIDO), the International Office for Migration (IOM), the UN Convention on Biodiversity (UNCBD), the UN Convention to Combat Desertification (UNCCD).

title: Voluntary Contributions to UN Agencies
description: Support is provided to a set of UN agencies whose work aligns closely to Ireland’s One World, One Future priorities on governance, human rights, social development and humanitarian action. Contributions to these UN agencies are generally un-earmarked (directed to their core budgets), allowing them to plan and manage resources effectively in support of the policy objectives set out in their strategic plans
